04160nam a22004575i 9781503616233DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221996cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036162337 a10.1515/97815036162332doi  a(DE-B1597)582617  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLAW0110002bisacsh1 aHuang, Philip C. C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCivil Justice in China :bRepresentation and Practice in the Qing /cPhilip C. C. Huang. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw, Society, and Culture in China00tFrontmatter -- tLaw, Society, and Culture in China -- tPreface -- tContents -- tTables -- tCHAPTER ONE Introduction -- tCHAPTER TWO Defining Categories: Disputes and Lawsuits in North China Villages Before the Communist Revolution -- tCHAPTER THREE Informal Justice: Mediation in North China Villages Before the Communist Revolution -- tCHAPTER FOUR Formal Justice: Codified Law and Magisterial Adjudication in the Qing -- tCHAPTER FIVE Between Informal Mediation and Formal Adjudication: The Third Realm of Qing Justice -- tCHAPTER SIX Two Patterns in the Qing Civil Justice System -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Extent, Cost, and Strategies of Litigation -- tCHAPTER EIGHT From the Perspective of Magistrate Handbooks -- tCHAPTER NINE Max Weber and the Qing Legal and Political Systems -- tAppendixes -- tAPPENDIX A Village and County Data -- tAPPENDIX B Weights and Measures -- tReferences -- tCharacter List -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo what extent do newly available case records bear out our conventional assumptions about the Qing legal system? Is it true, for example, that Qing courts rarely handled civil lawsuits—those concerned with disputes over land, debt, marriage, and inheritance—as official Qing representations led us to believe? Is it true that decent people did not use the courts? And is it true that magistrates generally relied more on moral predilections than on codified law in dealing with cases? Based in large part on records of 628 civil dispute cases from three counties from the 1760’s to the 1900’s, this book reexamines those widely accepted Qing representations in the light of actual practice. The Qing state would have had us believe that civil disputes were so “minor” or “trivial” that they were left largely to local residents themselves to resolve. However, case records show that such disputes actually made up a major part of the caseloads of local courts. The Qing state held that lawsuits were the result of actions of immoral men, but ethnographic information and case records reveal that when community/kin mediation failed, many common peasants resorted to the courts to assert and protect their legitimate claims. The Qing state would have had us believe that local magistrates, when they did deal with civil disputes, did so as mediators rather than judges. Actual records reveal that magistrates almost never engaged in mediation but generally adjudicated according to stipulations in the Qing code.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory -- Asian. 7aLAW / Civil Law.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361623340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503616233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503616233/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles